rdf:Description.lla:note: Certificate no: 20704. Ship owner: Jno. Davies, Aberyaron. Voyage from Cardiff to Bahia [state in Brazil], New York, Rio de Janeiro, Barbados, Savannah and South Shields. Journey statement notes that St. Paulo de Loanda was the intended destination (Luanda, Angola). Forms for Transmission of Seamen's Wages including John Forrest, George Henry Ley, James Williams and Apostle George.
Certificate no: 93.576. Ships called Jersey were registered in Cardiff and Jersey in 1883. Place of birth is Newport, Pembrokeshire.
Cyfarthfa was registered in Cardiff.
Several ships named Goudey were registered in Yarmouth, Nova Scotia in the 1880s including A Goudey, Annie Goudey, Ellen Goudey, Hattie Goudey, I H Goudey, Zebina Goudey.
Last ship probably Knight of St Patrick, registered in Liverpool 1881.
No record for Corsarla found. Ship name could be Corsanda, Corsande, Corsarle.
Last ship, Hudson, may be registered in Ipswich, West Hartlepool and Southampton as the name of port is not clear.
Place of birth could also read: Inbs hony or Subs rory/hony.
Carniola was registered at Digby, Nova Scotia.
Ceylon was registered in Windsor, Nova Scotia.

Note under certificates: 'David Singleton (Cook & Std) line 14. appears to have been accidentally drowned at Tybee while bathing. Have no cause to doubt the Master's report.' signed by N Welsh, M. M. Office, North Shields. Tybee is an island on the coast of Georgia, USA. Note: '(W & E safe herewith)'.
Cambusdoon was registered in St John, New Brunswick. Note: (Transmission scheme)
Place of birth is Saltcoats, Scotland. Ida C was registered at Hampton, Bermuda.

No Centenniel found although Centen(nial)s registered at St Andrews (New Brunswick), Port Medway (Nova Scotia), St Catherine's (Ontario), Sydney (Cape Breton Island) and St John (New Brunswick) in the 1880s. Location of Amer/Amen/Arnen/Arner unknown.

A ship called J F Chase was registered at Port of Spain, Trinidad in 1886, otherwise ship may be foreign. Location of Arner/Arnen/Amer unknown. Note under 'Certificates' - Joseph Dunn's desertion was recorded in the Official Log Book.
No record for Palamaris found.
Biela was registered in Liverpool 1880 as was Bida (alternative reading).
A Prince Regent was registered at St John, New Brunswick 1880.
A ship called Mondego was registered in Glasgow 1881. Release signature reads: Israel Vangorin.
No record for Jenetti or similar found in registered ships.
British Peer was registered in Liverpool 1880.
Ships named Arabella were registered in Gloucester, Caernarfon, Scarborough, Liverpool and Belfast in the 1880s.
